Capturing variables, and the effectively-final rule.

A lambda can reference local variables from the scope around it, but only under one condition: those variables must be effectively final, meaning they are assigned exactly once. The compiler will reject a lambda that reads a variable you reassign somewhere later, and it will reject a lambda that tries to assign to such a variable inside its own body.

Why the restriction? Because a lambda can outlive the method that created it. Picture handing a lambda to an executor that runs it later, on another thread entirely. A capturing lambda holds a snapshot of the value at the moment of capture. If the language let you reassign that variable afterwards, you would get confusing inconsistencies about which value the lambda actually sees.

There is a standard workaround when you genuinely need to mutate something a lambda touches. You wrap the value in a single-element array. The array reference itself never changes, so it stays effectively final, but you are free to mutate the contents of the array from inside the lambda. It is a little bit of a trick, and in real code you would usually reach for something cleaner, like an atomic integer, which we meet in the concurrency module.
